PASSAGES["Level 1"]=[{title:"My Cat",text:"I have a cat.\nMy cat is big.\nShe is soft and warm.\nShe can sit on my lap.\nShe can nap in the sun.\nI pet her every day.\nShe purrs when I pet her.\nI love my cat.",qs:["What can the cat do?","How does the cat feel when you pet her?","Do you have a pet? What is it like?"]},{title:"The Sun",text:"I see the sun.\nThe sun is up high.\nThe sun is hot.\nThe sun is big and round.\nIt gives us light.\nIt gives us heat.\nPlants need the sun.\nWe need the sun too.\nI like the sun.",qs:["What does the sun give us?","Why do plants need the sun?","What is your favorite thing to do on a sunny day?"]},{title:"My Ball",text:"I have a ball.\nIt is big and red.\nI kick the ball.\nIt goes far.\nI throw the ball up.\nIt comes back down.\nI roll it to my dog.\nMy dog runs after it.\nWe play all day.\nFun, fun, fun!",qs:["What color is the ball?","What are three things the child does with the ball?","What is your favorite game to play outside?"]}];
PASSAGES["Level 2"]=[{title:"My Dog",text:"I have a dog.\nHis name is Rex.\nRex has soft brown fur.\nHe can run very fast.\nHe can jump over logs.\nI throw a ball for him.\nHe runs to get it.\nHe brings it back to me.\nWe play for a long time.\nI love my dog Rex.",qs:["What is the dog's name?","What can Rex do?","How do you think the child feels about Rex? Why?"]},{title:"The Rain",text:"It is raining outside.\nI look out the window.\nThe rain falls fast.\nI put on my yellow coat.\nI put on my red boots.\nI run outside to play.\nI jump in the puddles.\nSplash! Splash! Splash!\nThe rain feels cool on my face.\nRainy days are so fun!",qs:["What does the child wear in the rain?","What does the child do outside?","Do you like rainy days? Why or why not?"]},{title:"At School",text:"I go to school every day.\nI walk with my friend Sam.\nWe sit down in our class.\nOur teacher reads us a book.\nThen we write in our journals.\nAt lunch we run and play.\nWe eat our food outside.\nIn the afternoon we do math.\nWhen the bell rings we go home.\nI can not wait to go back!",qs:["What do the children do in the morning at school?","What happens at lunch?","What is your favorite part of the school day?"]}];
PASSAGES["Level 3"]=[{title:"The Big Dog",text:"The big dog ran down the street.\nHe ran fast on his four legs.\nHe saw a man sitting on a bench.\nThe dog ran right up to the man.\nThe man reached out his hand.\nHe gave the dog a pat on the head.\nThe dog wagged his tail back and forth.\nHe licked the man on the hand.\nThe man smiled a big smile.\nThe dog was so happy to have a new friend.",qs:["Where did the dog run?","How did the dog show he was happy?","Have you ever made friends with a dog? What happened?"]},{title:"My Pet Fish",text:"I have a pet fish at home.\nHis name is Fin.\nFin lives in a big glass tank.\nHe is bright blue and red.\nHe swims around all day long.\nHe blows little bubbles in the water.\nEvery morning I feed him his food.\nI tap the tank and he swims up fast.\nHe opens his mouth for the flakes.\nFin is my favorite pet.",qs:["What does Fin look like?","What does Fin do when it is time to eat?","What makes a fish a good pet?"]},{title:"Time to Play",text:"The school bell rings at last.\nIt is time to go home!\nI grab my bag and run out the door.\nI wave to my friends on the way.\nFirst I ride my bike down the hill.\nThen I kick my ball in the yard.\nMy dog runs after the ball with me.\nWe chase each other all around.\nMom calls me in for dinner.\nWhat a great day it was!",qs:["What does the child do after school?","Why do you think the child says it was a great day?","What do you like to do after school?"]}];
PASSAGES["Level 4"]=[{title:"At the Park",text:"On Saturday we went to the park near our house. My sister and I ran across the grass as fast as we could. We found a pond with three big ducks swimming in it. The ducks had shiny green heads and bright orange feet. We had brought some bread from home. We broke it into small bits and tossed it to them. The ducks splashed and dove for every piece. After a while Mom called us for lunch. We walked home tired and happy.",qs:["What did the ducks look like?","What did the children feed the ducks?","Why do you think the children went home tired and happy?","What is your favorite thing to do at a park?"]},{title:"The Big Game",text:"Today was the day of our big soccer game. I put on my red jersey and laced up my cleats. My hands were shaking a little as we ran onto the field. The other team was fast and good. For a long time the score was zero to zero. Then my friend passed the ball right to my feet. I kicked it as hard as I could. It flew past the goalie and into the net! My whole team ran over and cheered. We won the game one to zero!",qs:["How did the child feel before the game?","What happened to win the game?","How do you think the team felt after winning?","What sport do you like to play?"]},{title:"My New Bike",text:"For my birthday I got a brand new bike. It was shiny red and black with silver handlebars. Dad helped me put on my helmet and knee pads. I climbed on and started to pedal down the street. At first I wobbled from side to side. Then I hit a crack in the road and fell down. My knee was sore but I did not cry. I got right back up and tried again. By the end of the afternoon I could ride all the way to the corner without falling. I was so proud of myself.",qs:["What did the bike look like?","What safety gear did the child wear?","What did the child do after falling?","Have you ever had to keep trying at something hard?"]}];
PASSAGES["Level 5"]=[{title:"The Lost Puppy",text:"One cool morning Jake was cutting through the park on his way to school. Near the swings he spotted a small brown puppy sitting all alone. It had no collar and its fur was muddy and wet. The puppy looked up at Jake with big scared eyes. Jake crouched down slowly and held out his hand. He broke off a piece of his sandwich and laid it on the ground. The puppy crept forward and sniffed it. Then it ate the piece right out of his hand. Jake gently picked it up and tucked it under his jacket. He turned around and headed home to tell his mom. That afternoon he made a lost dog poster and taped it to every telephone pole on the street.",qs:["Why did Jake move slowly toward the puppy?","What two things did Jake do to help the puppy?","What does this tell you about Jake as a person?","Have you ever helped an animal or person in need?"]},{title:"Pizza Night",text:"Every Friday evening is pizza night at the Morales house and everyone has a job to do. Dad starts by mixing the dough early in the afternoon and letting it rise. Mom makes the sauce from scratch using tomatoes from the garden. The three kids each get to choose their own toppings for their section of the pizza. Maya always picks pepperoni and extra cheese. Her brother Luis goes for mushrooms and olives every single time. When the timer goes off and Mom pulls the golden pizza from the oven the whole kitchen fills with the most amazing smell. Everyone agrees it is the best part of the week.",qs:["What does each family member do to help?","Why do you think pizza night is the best part of the week?","What does this story tell you about the Morales family?","What is a special food tradition in your family?"]},{title:"The Spelling Bee",text:"Carlos had been practicing for the regional spelling bee every single night for six weeks. He had flashcards covering his bedroom wall and made his mom quiz him during dinner. The morning of the contest his stomach felt like it was full of butterflies. Twenty students sat in a row on the gymnasium stage. One by one they walked to the microphone. When it was finally his turn Carlos walked up slowly, closed his eyes and took one deep breath. He thought about all those nights of practice. In the final round it was just Carlos and one other student. She misspelled the word ancient and sat down. Carlos stepped up and spelled it perfectly. The crowd burst into applause.",qs:["How did Carlos prepare for the spelling bee?","How did Carlos feel when it was his turn?","What made the difference for Carlos in the end?","What is something you have worked hard to get better at?"]}];
PASSAGES["Level 6"]=[{title:"The Soccer Star",text:"Mia had wanted to be a soccer player since she was four years old and first kicked a ball across the backyard. Now in fifth grade she practiced every single day after school, even when it rained and the field turned to mud. Her coach always said that talent gets you started but hard work gets you there. The day of the championship game finally arrived. Five hundred people filled the bleachers. Mia's stomach felt tight as she laced up her cleats. For the first half neither team scored. Then with three minutes left in the game Mia received a perfect pass near the top of the box. She took one touch to control it and then drove the ball low and hard toward the corner of the net. It curved past the goalkeeper's outstretched hands and hit the back of the net. Her teammates buried her in a pile. They had won.",qs:["What did Mia's coach always say about talent and hard work?","How did Mia feel before the game started?","What does the detail about practicing in the rain tell you about Mia?","What does this story teach about reaching a goal?"]},{title:"Rainy Day Inside",text:"The rain had been falling since before dawn and showed no signs of stopping. Sam pressed his face against the cold window and watched the drops race each other down the glass. His plans to ride bikes with his friends were ruined. He wandered into the kitchen where his mom was sorting through old cookbooks. She held one up and said they should try making something they had never made before. Sam pointed to a page with a photo of a glossy chocolate cake with three layers. His mom laughed and said why not. For the next two hours the kitchen became a floury messy wonderful disaster. Sam cracked eggs, measured vanilla, and took turns stirring the thick batter. When the cake finally came out of the oven and they spread chocolate frosting across the top Sam decided that rainy days might not be so bad after all.",qs:["How did Sam feel at the start of the story?","How did the rainy day change for Sam?","What details show that making the cake was not easy?","Has a bad day ever turned into a good one for you?"]},{title:"New Kid",text:"Starting at a new school in October felt like walking into a movie where everyone else already knew the plot. Sofia had moved three times in four years because of her dad's job and she was tired of being the new kid. She sat alone at lunch on the first day, carefully peeling the wrapper off her granola bar and trying to look like she did not mind. Then a girl with bright orange sneakers slid her tray onto the table across from her. Her name was Priya and she asked Sofia what her favorite video game was without any small talk or awkward pauses. Sofia told her and Priya said she had been trying to beat that same level for two weeks. They talked through the entire lunch period. By the time the bell rang Sofia had Priya's number in her phone. Being the new kid still was not easy. But it was easier than yesterday.",qs:["Why was Sofia tired of being the new kid?","What made Priya's approach different from what Sofia expected?","What does the last line mean?","Have you ever helped someone feel welcome or been helped yourself?"]}];
PASSAGES["Level 7"]=[{title:"Learning to Skate",text:"Marcus had watched his older cousin Jordan skate for years and made it look as effortless as walking. So when Marcus finally got his first skateboard for his twelfth birthday he assumed it would come naturally. It did not. The first time he stepped on the board in the driveway it shot out from under him and he landed hard on his hands and knees. He tried again and fell again. After the fifth fall he sat on the curb and thought seriously about giving up. Jordan sat down next to him and said something Marcus never forgot. He said that every single person who can skate right now has fallen more times than they can count. The only difference between someone who learns and someone who quits is what they do after they fall. Marcus stood up and tried again. Three weeks later he could ollie off the curb. Three months later he was teaching his little brother.",qs:["Why did Marcus think skating would be easy?","What did Jordan say that changed Marcus's thinking?","What does the ending of the story show about Marcus?","Describe a time you kept trying at something difficult."]},{title:"The Class Pet",text:"Room 14 had been debating the class pet question since September. A survey showed that fourteen students wanted a dog, eight wanted a rabbit, and three wanted a lizard. Ms. Chen explained patiently that a dog required too much space and supervision for a classroom. After much negotiation they settled on a dwarf hamster they named Nugget. Nugget quickly became the heart of the class. Students took turns cleaning the cage and tracking his exercise wheel rotations in a shared notebook. Then one Monday morning Ms. Chen arrived to find the cage door open and Nugget gone. The class spent the entire morning searching every corner of the room. Jaylen eventually found Nugget curled up inside a sneaker in the lost and found bin, apparently having squeezed under the classroom door during the night. The class agreed to invest in a better cage lock.",qs:["Why could the class not get a dog?","How did the students show responsibility for Nugget?","What character traits does Jaylen show in this story?","What do you think the class learned from this experience?"]},{title:"The Minecraft Build",text:"The project started as a casual comment between friends. Zoe told Ava she wished their school actually looked like a castle and Ava said they should just build one in Minecraft. What began as a joke turned into a six month obsession. Zoe handled architecture, designing towers and drawbridges from memory. Ava managed the interior, furnishing every classroom with bookshelves, maps, and glowing lanterns. They worked on it for two or three hours every weekend, sometimes arguing about details like whether the library should have a secret passage. It almost always did. When they finally invited their classmates into the world the reaction was overwhelming. Kids spent an hour just exploring. Several found hidden rooms that Zoe had never mentioned. One contained a chest with every student's name on a book inside it. Ava had added that detail without telling Zoe. It was the best surprise of the whole project.",qs:["How did the project begin?","How did Zoe and Ava divide their responsibilities?","What does Ava's secret addition to the world tell you about her?","Describe a creative project you worked hard on."]}];
PASSAGES["Level 8"]=[{title:"The Science Fair",text:"Destiny had always believed that her grandmother's habit of singing to her tomato plants was just a quirky personality trait. But when her science teacher announced the annual fair Destiny decided to find out if there was actually something to it. She designed a controlled experiment using two identical groups of bean seedlings grown under the same light and watering schedule. One group received an hour of classical music daily through a small speaker. The other group grew in silence. Destiny measured and recorded the height of each plant every three days for five weeks. At the end of the experiment the music group averaged 2.3 centimeters taller than the control group. When a judge asked how she came up with the idea Destiny smiled and said her grandmother had been her inspiration. She did not win first place but she earned something she valued more — a genuine scientific question and a real answer.",qs:["What was Destiny's hypothesis?","How did Destiny make her experiment fair?","What does the last sentence suggest about what Destiny values?","Design your own science fair experiment. What would you test?"]},{title:"Staying Safe Online",text:"The internet connects us to more information and more people than any previous generation could have imagined. But that connectivity comes with real risks that require real awareness. The most important rule of online safety is straightforward: never share identifying information such as your full name, school, address, phone number, or daily routine with people you have not met in person. This applies even when someone online seems friendly or claims to know your friends. Cyberbullying is another serious concern. Research shows that victims of online harassment are significantly more likely to experience anxiety and depression. If you see bullying happening online the most effective response is to not engage with the bully, save evidence by taking a screenshot, and report it to a trusted adult. Remember that anything you post online can be copied and shared without your permission. Ask yourself before posting: would I be comfortable if my teacher or parent saw this?",qs:["What is the most important rule of online safety according to the passage?","What three steps should you take if you see cyberbullying?","Why does the author suggest imagining your teacher seeing your post?","What is one thing you could do to make your own online habits safer?"]},{title:"The Big Move",text:"The morning Theo's parents told him they were moving to a new city Theo went to his room, closed the door, and did not come out for dinner. He had lived in the same house his entire life. His best friend Marcus lived four houses down. He had made the travel baseball team for the first time this year. None of that would exist in the new city. For weeks afterward Theo answered questions with one or two words and spent most evenings in his room. Then on his first day at the new school his English teacher asked students to share one interesting fact about themselves. Theo mentioned almost by accident that he was a huge fan of the city's minor league baseball team. Three boys sitting nearby turned around at the same time. By Friday Theo had traded numbers with all three of them and had plans to attend a game the following weekend. He still missed Marcus. He probably always would. But the new city was starting to feel slightly less like a foreign country.",qs:["Why was the move so hard for Theo specifically?","What does Theo's behaviour in the weeks after the news tell us?","What does the ending suggest about adapting to change?","Describe a time you had to adjust to a big change."]}];
PASSAGES["Level 9"]=[{title:"How Sneakers Became Culture",text:"For most of the twentieth century athletic shoes were functional objects — designed to protect feet during sport and nothing more. That began to change in 1984 when Nike signed a twenty-one year old rookie named Michael Jordan to an endorsement deal worth 2.5 million dollars over five years. The Air Jordan 1 released that year was banned by the NBA for violating uniform colour rules. Nike paid the fine for every game Jordan wore them and turned the controversy into a marketing campaign. Suddenly sneakers carried a message beyond athletics. They became symbols of identity, status, and belonging. The resale market that followed was unprecedented. Shoes that sold for 65 dollars in 1985 routinely sell for thousands today. The most coveted releases generate lineups that stretch around city blocks. What Nike understood before almost anyone else was that people do not just want to own objects. They want to own meaning.",qs:["Why did the NBA ban the Air Jordan 1?","How did Nike turn the ban into an advantage?","What does the author mean when he says people want to own meaning?","Can you think of another product that carries meaning beyond its function?"]},{title:"Simone Biles",text:"By any statistical measure Simone Biles is the greatest gymnast in the history of the sport. She has won more World Championship medals than any other gymnast and has four signature moves named after her in the sport's official code of points — an honour reserved for skills so difficult that only the person who invented them has successfully competed them. What makes her story more remarkable is its beginning. Biles was placed in foster care at age three after her mother was unable to care for her and her siblings. Her grandparents eventually adopted her. She discovered gymnastics almost by accident on a field trip at age six. At the 2020 Tokyo Olympics, competing with the entire world watching, Biles made the decision to withdraw from several events to protect her mental health. The response was polarizing, but many athletes and mental health advocates called it the most courageous act of her career — harder in some ways than any skill she had ever performed.",qs:["What makes Biles statistically the greatest gymnast ever?","How did her childhood shape who she became?","Why did some people call her Tokyo decision her most courageous act?","What does Biles's story suggest about what it means to be strong?"]},{title:"The Robot That Learned to Walk",text:"Teaching a robot to walk sounds simple until you try. Human walking involves hundreds of tiny muscular adjustments per second, constant recalibration of balance, and an unconscious understanding of physics that took us years of childhood to develop. Engineers at a leading robotics lab spent two years and seventeen prototype versions trying to replicate it. Version one fell immediately upon activation. Version nine could take three steps before toppling. Each failure generated reams of data that engineers fed back into their models. They adjusted weight distribution, reprogrammed balance algorithms, and redesigned the ankle joints. Version seventeen finally crossed the lab floor without falling. The project leader said the hardest part was not the engineering. It was convincing the team to treat every failure as information rather than defeat. That mindset, he argued, is the difference between scientists and people who used to want to be scientists.",qs:["Why is human walking difficult to replicate in a robot?","How did the engineers use their failures?","What did the project leader mean by treating failure as information?","How could this mindset apply to something challenging in your own life?"]}];
PASSAGES["Level 10"]=[{title:"The Science of Slime",text:"Non-Newtonian fluids occupy a strange middle ground between solids and liquids, behaving differently depending on the force applied to them. Cornstarch mixed with water is a classic example. Apply slow gentle pressure and it flows like a liquid. Strike it quickly and it resists like a solid. The slime that became a viral sensation among children in the mid-2010s operates on similar principles. Most recipes combine polyvinyl acetate, the polymer found in white school glue, with a cross-linking agent such as sodium borate. The borate ions form chemical bridges between the long glue polymer chains, restricting their movement without stopping it entirely. The result is a substance with variable viscosity that stretches, bounces, and holds its shape depending on how it is handled. Materials scientists use similar principles to develop body armour, shock-absorbing padding in athletic helmets, and industrial dampening systems. The children making slime on YouTube are, perhaps unknowingly, conducting genuine polymer chemistry.",qs:["What makes a non-Newtonian fluid different from regular liquids?","How does the cross-linking agent change the glue?","What real-world applications use similar principles to slime?","What does the final sentence suggest about everyday experiments?"]},{title:"Why Dogs Are Good for You",text:"The bond between humans and dogs stretches back at least fifteen thousand years, making it one of the oldest interspecies relationships on record. Modern science is now quantifying what dog owners have always suspected: the relationship is genuinely good for human health. Studies have shown that interacting with a dog for as little as ten minutes significantly reduces cortisol, the body's primary stress hormone, while simultaneously increasing oxytocin, sometimes called the bonding hormone. Dog owners also walk an average of twenty-two minutes more per day than non-owners, contributing to measurably lower rates of cardiovascular disease. In educational settings therapy dogs have produced particularly striking results. Students who read aloud to trained therapy dogs show reduced anxiety and improved fluency compared to those who read to adults. Researchers believe this occurs because dogs offer non-judgmental attention, eliminating the social anxiety that often accompanies reading aloud. The dog simply listens.",qs:["What two hormones are affected by interacting with dogs?","Why do therapy dogs help struggling readers specifically?","What does the phrase non-judgmental attention mean in this context?","What other situations might benefit from non-judgmental support?"]},{title:"How Animation Works",text:"The magic of animation rests on a quirk of human perception called the persistence of vision. When the eye sees a rapid sequence of still images — faster than roughly twelve frames per second — the brain interprets them as continuous motion rather than a series of separate pictures. Early animators at studios like Disney exploited this phenomenon by drawing each frame of a film by hand on transparent celluloid sheets called cels. A single minute of finished animation required roughly 1,440 individual drawings. Feature films took years to complete and employed hundreds of artists. The transition to computer animation beginning in the 1980s changed the tools but not the underlying principle. Pixar's first feature film Toy Story, released in 1995, was rendered entirely by computers but still required teams of animators to choreograph every movement. Today a single frame of a major animated film can take up to 100 hours to render. The technology has transformed but the commitment to creating believable motion, frame by frame, has not.",qs:["What is the persistence of vision?","How many drawings did one minute of early animation require?","What stayed the same between traditional and computer animation?","Why do you think animation takes so long even with modern computers?"]}];
PASSAGES["Level 11"]=[{title:"How MrBeast Makes Videos",text:"Jimmy Donaldson, known online as MrBeast, began uploading YouTube videos at thirteen from his childhood bedroom in Greenville, North Carolina. For the first four years almost nobody watched. His early videos counting to one hundred thousand and estimating the wealth of other YouTubers attracted tiny audiences. What separated Donaldson from the millions of other aspiring creators was not immediate talent but relentless analysis. He watched thousands of hours of successful videos, took notes on what made people click and stay, and applied those observations methodically to his own content. By the time he began staging elaborate challenges and large-scale giveaways he had already developed an instinct for what would perform. His philanthropic projects, including funding surgeries for people who could not afford them, planting twenty million trees, and opening free food banks, grew organically from his platform rather than being added as a strategy. Donaldson has said that the goal was never fame but impact, and that the audience followed the impact. His channel now represents one of the most significant media brands built by a single individual in the internet era.",qs:["What did Donaldson do during the years when almost nobody watched?","What does the passage suggest was the real reason for his success?","How does the passage characterize the relationship between his philanthropy and his fame?","What does his story suggest about patience and long-term thinking?"]},{title:"What Happens When You Sleep",text:"Sleep is not a passive state of unconsciousness but an active and essential biological process. During the deepest stages of sleep the brain cycles through a remarkable series of maintenance tasks. Memories formed during the day are consolidated and transferred from short-term to long-term storage, which is why sleep deprivation immediately before an exam is counterproductive despite feeling like extra study time. Growth hormone, which is critical for tissue repair and muscle development, is released almost exclusively during deep sleep. The immune system uses sleep to produce cytokines, proteins that help fight infection and inflammation. Adolescents require eight to ten hours of sleep per night for optimal function, yet surveys consistently show that most teenagers get significantly less. A primary culprit is the blue light emitted by screens, which suppresses melatonin production and delays the onset of sleep by signalling to the brain that it is still daytime. The consequences of chronic sleep deprivation extend beyond tiredness, affecting mood regulation, decision-making, and long-term cardiovascular health.",qs:["Why is studying instead of sleeping before an exam counterproductive?","What three functions does the body perform during deep sleep?","How does blue light affect sleep onset?","What changes could you make to improve your own sleep?"]},{title:"The History of Video Games",text:"The video game industry began not in a corporate boardroom but in the physics laboratories of American universities in the 1950s and 60s, where researchers built simple interactive programs as demonstrations of computing power. The first commercially successful arcade game, Pong, released by Atari in 1972, consisted of two rectangles and a moving square on a black screen. Lines formed around the arcade cabinet anyway. The introduction of home consoles beginning with the Atari 2600 in 1977 moved gaming from public spaces into living rooms and created a new form of family entertainment. The industry crashed spectacularly in 1983 due to market oversaturation and a flood of poor-quality games, then recovered with the arrival of Nintendo in 1985. Each subsequent decade brought exponential leaps: three-dimensional graphics in the 1990s, online multiplayer in the 2000s, mobile gaming in the 2010s. Today the global video game industry generates more revenue annually than the film and music industries combined. Competitive gaming, known as esports, fills stadiums and awards prize pools in the millions. The rectangle and the moving square have come a long way.",qs:["Where did the first video games originate and why?","What caused the industry crash of 1983?","How does the final sentence connect to the rest of the passage?","What do you think the next major development in gaming will be?"]}];
PASSAGES["Level 12"]=[{title:"What It Takes to Be a Content Creator",text:"The popular image of the content creator — someone who films themselves doing things they enjoy and gets paid handsomely for it — obscures a more complicated reality. Successful creators consistently identify consistency as the factor that separates those who break through from those who do not. Most channels that now have millions of subscribers posted for twelve to twenty-four months before experiencing meaningful growth. During that period the work is identical to what comes after: scripting, filming, editing, publishing, analysing performance data, and repeating. The difference is that in the early phase almost no one is watching. This requires a psychological resilience that many aspiring creators underestimate. Beyond consistency, top creators treat content production as a data-driven enterprise. They study which thumbnails generate clicks, which topics retain viewers longest, and which posting times reach the largest audience. The romantic notion of simply sharing a passion and letting the audience find you is, with rare exceptions, a myth. What actually works is passion combined with discipline, curiosity combined with analysis, and the willingness to keep publishing long after the initial enthusiasm has faded.",qs:["Why does the author say the popular image of content creation is misleading?","What does the passage identify as the most important factor for success?","What does the author mean by treating content as a data-driven enterprise?","Do you think passion alone is enough to succeed at something? Why or why not?"]},{title:"Climate Change and Weather",text:"One of the most persistent misunderstandings in public discourse about climate change involves confusing weather with climate. Weather describes atmospheric conditions at a specific place and time — a blizzard in Buffalo, a heat wave in Phoenix, a rainy Tuesday in Vancouver. Climate describes the long-term statistical patterns of weather in a region over decades. Because weather is what people experience directly and personally it is the frame through which most people interpret climate data, which leads to a logical error. A cold winter in one location does not contradict a global warming trend any more than one poor test score negates a student's overall academic record. The relevant data operates at a different scale entirely. Global average surface temperatures have risen approximately 1.2 degrees Celsius since pre-industrial times. That figure sounds modest, but climate systems are highly sensitive to small changes in average temperature. The consequences include shifts in precipitation patterns, accelerating glacial melt, rising sea levels, increased frequency and intensity of extreme weather events, and disruptions to agricultural cycles that billions of people depend on.",qs:["What is the difference between weather and climate?","Why does the author use the analogy of a test score?","What consequences does the passage link to a 1.2 degree rise in temperature?","Why do you think people find it difficult to think about climate at a global scale?"]},{title:"The Real Story of Thanksgiving",text:"The Thanksgiving narrative taught in most American schools — a harmonious feast between Pilgrims and Native Americans celebrating cooperation and gratitude — is a substantially simplified version of a complicated historical moment. The 1621 harvest celebration at Plymouth Colony did involve both English settlers and members of the Wampanoag Confederacy, and historical records suggest it lasted three days. But the relationship between the two groups was shaped primarily by mutual necessity rather than friendship. The Pilgrims had lost nearly half their number to disease and starvation during their first winter, and the Wampanoag leader Ousamequin saw alliance with the settlers as a strategic counterweight to rival tribes. The warm multicultural narrative became culturally dominant much later. Thanksgiving was not declared a national holiday until 1863, when Abraham Lincoln used it to promote unity during the Civil War. The holiday's mythology was largely constructed in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. Understanding this history does not require abandoning gratitude as a value. It requires holding complexity alongside tradition.",qs:["What motivated the Wampanoag to ally with the Pilgrims?","When did Thanksgiving become a national holiday and why then?","What does the author mean by holding complexity alongside tradition?","Why do you think simplified historical narratives persist even when the full story is known?"]}];
PASSAGES["Level 13"]=[{title:"How Chocolate Is Made",text:"Chocolate begins its journey not in a factory but in a tropical rainforest. The cacao tree, which grows only within twenty degrees of the equator, produces large colourful pods directly on its trunk and branches. Inside each pod are between twenty and fifty seeds called cacao beans, surrounded by a sweet white pulp. Farmers harvest the pods by hand using machetes, then split them open to remove the beans. The beans are piled into wooden boxes and covered with banana leaves, where they ferment for five to seven days. Fermentation is a critical step that develops the complex flavours we associate with chocolate. After fermentation the beans are dried in the sun for another week, then shipped to chocolate manufacturers around the world. At the factory the beans are roasted at high temperatures, which deepens their flavour and loosens the outer shell. The shells are removed and the inner pieces, called nibs, are ground into a thick paste called chocolate liquor. Despite its name, chocolate liquor contains no alcohol. It is simply pure ground cacao. This paste can be pressed to separate cocoa butter from cocoa powder, or combined with sugar, milk, and additional cocoa butter to produce the chocolate bars we enjoy today.",qs:["Where do cacao trees grow and why?","Why is fermentation described as a critical step?","What is chocolate liquor and why might its name be confusing?","What does this passage suggest about how much work goes into everyday foods?"]},{title:"How Volcanoes Work",text:"A volcano is essentially an opening in the Earth's crust through which molten rock, gases, and ash can escape from deep within the planet. To understand why volcanoes exist, you need to understand the structure of the Earth itself. Beneath the thin rocky crust we live on lies the mantle, a layer of rock so hot that it flows slowly like an extremely thick liquid over millions of years. This molten rock is called magma. In certain locations, magma collects in underground chambers and builds up pressure over time. When the pressure becomes great enough, the magma forces its way toward the surface through cracks and weaknesses in the crust. Once magma reaches the surface it is called lava. Some volcanoes erupt explosively, sending columns of ash and rock kilometres into the atmosphere. Others release lava in slow-moving rivers that can travel for kilometres before cooling and hardening into new rock. The Hawaiian islands were formed entirely by volcanic activity over millions of years, as lava built up layer by layer on the ocean floor until it broke the surface. Volcanoes are destructive forces, but they also create new land, enrich soil with minerals, and have shaped the continents we live on.",qs:["What is the difference between magma and lava?","How were the Hawaiian islands formed?","Why do some volcanoes explode while others release slow lava flows?","What does the passage suggest about the dual nature of volcanoes?"]},{title:"The Science of Sleep",text:"Sleep might look like doing nothing, but your brain and body are extraordinarily busy during those hours. Scientists have identified several distinct stages of sleep that the brain cycles through multiple times each night. The deepest stages are when your body does most of its physical repair work, releasing growth hormone that helps build and restore muscle and tissue. This is why athletes and growing children need more sleep than most adults. The rapid eye movement stage, known as REM sleep, is when most dreaming occurs. During REM sleep your brain is nearly as active as when you are awake, consolidating memories and processing emotions from the day. Without adequate REM sleep people often feel emotionally fragile and have difficulty concentrating. The recommended amount of sleep varies by age. Children between six and twelve years old need nine to twelve hours per night. Teenagers need eight to ten. Most adults function best on seven to nine hours. One of the most common sleep disruptors today is exposure to blue light from screens in the hour before bed. Blue light signals to the brain that it is still daytime, suppressing the release of melatonin, the hormone that triggers sleepiness. Simply putting screens away an hour before bed can significantly improve both how quickly you fall asleep and the quality of sleep you get.",qs:["What happens in the body during the deepest stages of sleep?","What is REM sleep and why is it important?","How does blue light affect sleep?","What changes could you make to improve your own sleep based on this passage?"]}];
PASSAGES["Level 14"]=[{title:"How Planes Fly",text:"The fact that a machine weighing hundreds of thousands of kilograms can lift itself off the ground and cruise at nearly a thousand kilometres per hour at an altitude of twelve kilometres is, when you stop to think about it, remarkable. The secret lies in a principle discovered by Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli in the eighteenth century. An airplane wing is shaped so that its upper surface is curved while its lower surface is relatively flat. When air flows over the wing, it must travel a greater distance over the curved top than across the flat bottom in the same amount of time. To cover that greater distance, the air on top moves faster. Bernoulli discovered that faster-moving air exerts less pressure than slower-moving air. This means the air rushing over the top of the wing pushes down with less force than the slower air beneath pushes up. The result is a net upward force called lift. For lift to work, the wing must be moving through the air fast enough. This is why planes need long runways to accelerate before takeoff. Once in the air, the engines provide thrust to maintain speed, the wings provide lift to maintain altitude, and the pilots use moveable surfaces on the wings and tail to control direction. Modern commercial aircraft are also shaped to minimize drag, the resistance force that air creates against any object moving through it.",qs:["What is Bernoulli's principle and how does it explain lift?","Why do planes need runways to take off?","What four forces act on an airplane in flight?","What does this passage suggest about the relationship between science and engineering?"]},{title:"The History of Basketball",text:"Basketball is one of the few major sports with a known inventor and a precise birth date. On December 1, 1891, a Canadian physical education instructor named James Naismith nailed two peach baskets to a gymnasium balcony in Springfield, Massachusetts, and wrote thirteen rules for a new indoor game. His goal was modest: to give his students a vigorous activity to keep them occupied during the winter months when outdoor sports were impossible. The original game looked quite different from the modern version. Players could not dribble — they had to pass or shoot from wherever they caught the ball. The peach baskets had solid bottoms, so someone had to climb a ladder to retrieve the ball after every successful shot. Within a year the game had spread to YMCAs across North America. By 1936 it was an Olympic sport. The NBA was founded in 1946 and grew slowly through the 1950s and 1960s before television transformed it into a major entertainment industry. The arrival of players like Magic Johnson and Larry Bird in the 1980s revived a struggling league, and Michael Jordan's dominance in the 1990s made basketball a genuinely global sport. Today the NBA draws players from over forty countries and broadcasts games to more than two hundred nations.",qs:["Why did Naismith invent basketball?","How was the original game different from modern basketball?","What two things transformed basketball into a global sport?","What does Naismith's story suggest about how great ideas often begin?"]},{title:"Why Cats Purr",text:"The purr is one of the most recognizable sounds in the animal kingdom, and for centuries humans assumed they understood it completely. Cats purr when they are content, we said, and left it at that. The reality turns out to be considerably more interesting. Cats produce purring through a rapid movement of the muscles in their larynx, which causes the glottis — the part of the larynx surrounding the vocal cords — to dilate and constrict rapidly as the cat breathes in and out. This produces the characteristic rhythmic rumble at frequencies typically between 25 and 150 hertz. While cats certainly do purr when relaxed and happy, research has shown they also purr when stressed, injured, giving birth, or even dying. Scientists now believe purring serves multiple functions. It is a form of communication, signalling to humans and other cats that the cat is not a threat. But it may also be a form of self-medication. Studies have found that the specific frequencies of a cat's purr fall within a range known to promote bone density and healing in mammals. Cats, who spend a significant portion of their lives resting, may have evolved purring partly as a low-energy mechanism to keep their bones and muscles healthy during long periods of inactivity.",qs:["How do cats physically produce a purr?","Why was the original explanation for purring incomplete?","What two main functions does purring serve according to researchers?","What does this passage suggest about making assumptions based on incomplete observation?"]}];
PASSAGES["Level 15"]=[{title:"How Video Games Are Made",text:"The video game you play in an afternoon took hundreds of people several years to build. The development of a major game typically begins not with code or artwork but with a concept document — a written description of what the game will feel like, who the characters are, and what players will actually do. From this document a small team of designers build a prototype, a rough playable version that tests whether the core idea is actually fun. Many promising concepts are abandoned at this stage because they simply do not work in practice. If the prototype succeeds, the project expands. Artists create concept drawings of every character, environment, and object in the game. Programmers write hundreds of thousands of lines of code that govern how every element behaves. Sound designers record and create thousands of audio effects. Voice actors record dialogue. Composers write original music. All of these elements must work together without errors in a final product that might contain hundreds of hours of content. Testing is a critical and often underappreciated phase. Teams of testers play the game repeatedly, documenting every flaw, inconsistency, or crash. Major games go through thousands of reported bugs before release. Even after launch, developers continue releasing updates to fix problems and add content. The game you download on release day is often significantly different from the version that ships a year later.",qs:["Why do some game concepts get abandoned at the prototype stage?","What does the passage suggest about the relationship between creativity and testing?","Name four different types of specialists who work on a major game.","What does this passage reveal about what it means to make something look easy?"]},{title:"The Amazing World of Ants",text:"There are approximately twenty quadrillion ants on Earth — that is twenty million billion — and their combined weight is estimated to roughly equal the combined weight of all humans. This staggering abundance is not accidental. Ants have been extraordinarily successful for over one hundred million years because of one defining characteristic: cooperation. An individual ant is a simple creature with a very small brain, capable of only basic behaviours. But a colony of ants, which can number in the millions, functions as something closer to a single intelligent organism. Individual ants communicate primarily through chemicals called pheromones, leaving trails that direct other ants to food sources and signalling alarm when danger is near. Different ants within a colony have specialized roles. Worker ants forage and maintain the nest. Soldier ants defend the colony. The queen, whose sole function is reproduction, can live for decades and lay millions of eggs in her lifetime. Leafcutter ants cultivate underground fungus gardens, farming their own food in a practice that predates human agriculture by millions of years. Army ants cooperate to form living structures — bridges, rafts, and protective walls — using only their own bodies linked together. What appears to be intelligent planning is actually the emergent result of thousands of individuals each following simple chemical signals.",qs:["What does the author mean by emergent behaviour?","How do leafcutter ants demonstrate sophistication?","Why does the author say a colony is like a single intelligent organism?","What does the success of ants suggest about the power of cooperation?"]},{title:"How Mountains Form",text:"Mountains are so permanent in human experience that it is difficult to imagine them as anything other than fixed features of the landscape. But mountains are in constant, if imperceptibly slow, motion — rising, eroding, and in some cases disappearing entirely over geological timescales. The primary mechanism that builds mountains is the movement of tectonic plates, the massive sections of the Earth's crust that float on the semi-molten mantle beneath. The Earth's surface is divided into about fifteen major plates that move between one and fifteen centimetres per year — roughly the speed at which fingernails grow. When two continental plates collide, neither is dense enough to sink beneath the other. Instead, the crust crumples and folds upward like a slow-motion car crash, building mountain ranges that can reach kilometres in height. The Himalayas, which contain the world's highest peaks including Mount Everest, formed this way when the Indian subcontinent collided with Asia approximately fifty million years ago and continues to push northward today, meaning Everest is still technically growing. Mountains also form through volcanic activity, where magma pushes through the crust and builds up over millions of eruptions. The Cascade Range in North America formed this way. As soon as mountains form, erosion begins wearing them down through wind, water, ice, and gravity. Ancient mountain ranges like the Appalachians were once as tall as the Himalayas but have been reduced over hundreds of millions of years to gentle hills.",qs:["What causes continental plates to build mountains when they collide?","Why are the Himalayas still growing?","How do volcanic mountains differ from collision mountains in the way they form?","What does the passage suggest about our everyday perception of permanence?"]}];
